<TITLE> 3 water transport strikers remanded </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 11 (bdnews24.com)  A Dhaka court granted police one day to interrogate three members of the dissenting Noujan Sramik Federation, including its acting president. The three, accused of vandalising offices of the pro-government group of water transport workers, the Noujan Sramik League, were produced before the court on Tuesday afternoon. Dhaka Chief Metropolitan Magistrates Court judge Abdul Mazid, on Tuesday, granted the Kotwali police one day to grill the detainees including the organisation's president Shah Alam. Sadarghat police camp's sub-inspector Mozammel Haque had asked for four days. Following the hearing, the court rejected Shah Alam's bail petition and granted one day remand. Shah Alam was arrested on Monday noon on charges of attacking and vandalising the Noujan Shoromik League's office and damaging the prime minister's photo. The police also arrested two employees of Koko-5, a water vessel, Md Taher and Monir, members of the federation. Sub-inspector Md Babul Mia, general recording officer of police, confirmed bdnews24.com about the one-day remand of the three accused. A case was filed on May 7 with the Kotwali police. bdnew
